  <p>
    The result of all this was a sound that broke the rules of high-fidelity
    recording and, in doing so, created something with more emotional fidelity
    than any clean, separated mix could achieve. The Wall of Sound was not about
    hearing the instruments. It was about feeling them.
  </p>
